No test accounts are required. Yunque has no login system, no user
accounts, and no server component of any kind - it's a local Markdown
editor that reads and writes files on the tester's own machine.

FIRST LAUNCH: On first launch, Yunque shows a one-time End User License
Agreement screen that must be accepted (checkbox + "Accept" button)
before the app becomes usable. This is expected behavior, not a bug.

EXPORT FEATURE: Yunque includes an optional "Export" feature (icon in
the left sidebar) that converts the open document to PDF, DOCX, HTML,
ODT, or plain text. This feature requires pandoc
(https://pandoc.org), a separate open-source program, to be installed
on the machine - Yunque does not bundle it. If pandoc is not installed
on the test machine, clicking Export and choosing a format will show an
error message explaining that pandoc could not be found. This is
expected behavior, not a malfunction. To fully test Export, install
pandoc first (a simple installer is available at
https://pandoc.org/installing.html), or the feature can be skipped
during review, as it does not affect any other part of the app.

No features are hidden, conditional, or require unlocking. No
dependencies on other Microsoft or third-party products besides the
optional pandoc integration described above.
